The President of the United States, Joe Biden, addressed the U.S.-African Leaders Summit at the Walter E. Washington Convention Center in Washington, D.C. He expressed his gratitude for the leaders attending and conveyed his condolences to the Democratic Republic of the Congo for the loss of life due to flooding. Biden emphasized the importance of cooperation between the United States and Africa and highlighted the need for African voices and leadership in global discussions and institutions. He announced a commitment of $55 billion over the next three years to support Africa's priorities and the African Union's Agenda 2063. Biden also discussed the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic and Russia's actions in Ukraine on global development, stating that it is more urgent than ever to take decisive action together. He pledged to lead with American values, including support for democracy, human rights, and responsible government. Biden announced initiatives to counter democratic backsliding, strengthen transparent governance, and enhance security cooperation. He also mentioned the establishment of the President's Advisory Council on African Diaspora Engagement and expressed his eagerness to visit African countries. Biden concluded by assuring the leaders that the United States is committed to delivering on its commitments and working closely with African nations and the African Union to fulfill the aspirations of Agenda 2063.